 edge of your chair.";i:38;s:89:"Get your arm rest out of the way on the side next to the surface you are transferring to.";i:39;s:24:"Lean your trunk forward.";i:40;s:79:"When transferring your head should move in the opposite direction of your hips.";i:41;s:92:"This is known as a head-hips relationship and can help with movement and clearing obstacles.";i:42;s:100:"Wheelchair to Toilet Transfer Techniques For Wheelchair Transfers involving a wheelchair and toilet.";i:43;s:285:"We recommend having a raised toilet seat with arms a raised toilet seat with arms helps ease this type of wheelchair transfer because it helps the wheelchair user by giving them something to hold onto for support this will allow the transfer to be made with extreme caution and safety.";i:44;s:39:"Two people work together on this carry.";i:45;s:83:"Stand on either side of the victim who is sitting up on the edge of a bed or chair.";i:46;s:72:"Each of you places one hand behind the victims back and clasp shoulders.";i:47;s:65:"Place your other hands under the patients knees and clasp wrists.";i:48;s:65:"Lift up the victim and carry out making yourselves a human chair.";i:49;s:107:"Some older chair lifts use a conveyor belt as you get on the lift enabling the lift to travel a bit faster.";i:50;s:115:"Chair lifts also vary in the number of seats they have with most chair lifts normally having between 2 and 8 seats.";i:51;s:75:"The last major difference there can be is the type of safety bar they have.";i:52;s:161:"Adjust the bed to make transfers easier General Safety Rules Whenever possible use your body weight and momentum to move patient rather than muscle a patient up.";i:53;s:84:"Place feet shoulder width apart or one foot in front of another to make a wide base.";i:54;s:25:"Do not lean over patient.";i:55;s:48:"A NEWER VERSION OF THIS SKILL CAN BE FOUND HERE.";i:56;s:62:"Httpsyoutube_irfJdCL2DwTHIS IS AN OLDER VERSION OF THIS SKILL.";i:57;s:40:"View how this skill should look when pe.";i:5